      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Etadanik Mistmorgue</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Posted this in the general forum too.  Please feel free to discuss / comment.</P><P>With the introduction of Luclin, Verant gave classes AA skills to allow them to continue building their characters (it was also, as I recall, meant to differentiate players of the same class by allowing them to specialize but that has gone down the drain b/c of no limits to how much AA class skills you can get). Now this is a great idea, and for some classes it has become a boon so great that it revolutionarized their playing style. The problem, however, lies in what I suppose could be called a lack of understanding in class-specific problems. The best AA skill is not the skill that allows a class to step on another class's toes - that is, IMO, antithesis to EQ's theory of classes. Rather, the best AA skills are the ones that complement the class, being an improvement over what they already have or a feature that makes it easier for them to do what they already do. With that said, let's examine the necro AA skills:</P><P>AA Call to Corpse: this is a great skill at times and easily complements an existing necro ability; the only problem with this skill is its proposed cost in terms of AAs. Even then, it is arguable that a lot of AA skills that cost more than this skill is in actuality a lot worse.</P><P>Suggested replacement: None</P><P>AA Dead Mesmerization: this is a worthless skill. First, it complements no existing necro ability because it is NOT an upgrade to screaming terror, is AE as opposed to single-target, AND is undead-only. It does not help the necro as a crowd controller even in an undead area because of its absurd re-use time. It does not serve to do anything for the class but being a toy you can amaze friends with. It is, as such, a failed AA skill.</P><P>Suggested replacement: either an upgrade to screaming terror or a single-target undead mez that allows us to lock-down two undead mobs without an effort, and 4-5 with ST.</P><P>AA Dire Charm: There are two things wrong with this skill. First, let's look at its intended purpose: it is *intended* to serve as a natural upgrade to the necro's line of undead charm spells, which mirrors the enchanter's line of general purpose charm spells. There is a BIG problem with this: the level 46 limit. For an enchanter, the level 46 limit is nothing because almost every zone in the game barring the most uber of raid zones and planes have SOME kind of level 46 mob that the enchanter can charm. A necro, on the other hand, has maybe 5 zones in the ENTIRE game where Dire Charm could serve a purpose. In those particular zones, a necro with dire charm surpasses a necro with the EoT in terms of raw power, but often NOT in terms of exp-gain. This means that Dire Charm is only nice in the idea that it can increase our DPS in a group or help us solo some slightly bigger mobs. It does not do to us what it does to enchanters. It completely changes their class, while it barely modifies ours. To put it short: this skill is much too situational. </P><P>Secondly, what does this spell ADD to our class? Necromancers have ALWAYS been a strong pet class - Dire Charm has the potential to, of course, produce a much stronger pet than the EoT, but this pet steals exp like no other. In the enchanter's case, not only is this skill NOT merely situational, but it is also a HUGE addition to their class that they simply did not have before. Dire Charm, which to enchanters is a EXP MINE, is of rather dubious use for a necromancer in exp-gain. To us, it is more of a farming skill or, in some cases, a reason for us to get groups. </P><P>Suggested replacement: In sumarry, Dire Charm is overpriced for the skill that it is. It should *not* cost 9 AAxp points. The maximum it should cost is 6. Even so, I do not think Dire Charm: undead is a very well-thought of skill and moreover that it should not be considered the necro uber skill at all, unlike the enchanter's version (which to them is the most uber thing to ever exist in this game). I personally abhor the idea of giving a watered down version of another class's AA skill to another - a class's AA skill should be UNIQUE to that class, not a hand-me-down from another class.</P><P>AA Fearstorm: Another worthless skill. The necro's Fear line of spells are single-target because our class is a single-target-orientated class. We are not wizards or druids who quad-kite - we focus on one mob and use our single-target spells to bring it down fast and efficiently. Therefore, AA Fearstorm adds nothing to the fear-line. Now let's consider its potential as an escape spell: every necro escape spell in the game has a recast timer that is its greatest limit, and for Fearstorm it is the worst limit of them all. At 72 minutes, Fearstorm is such a situational spell that to spend 5 points on it is a waste. Since fear is worthless against level 55+ mobs and Fearstorm will bring a HUGE train unless you're fighting mobs lower than level 50, you might say that this spell's only worth is in saving you/your group from a horde of angry frogloks from sebilis the AE group trained on you. </P><P>Suggested replacement: There are several necro escape spells that could serve excellently as the model for this skill if it was meant to be an escape skill. A instant-FD (but one that requires like 10 mins to reuse), a Quivering Veil that heals you to full, or even simply Improved FD Chances or Lower FD Refresh Rate would all be excellent additions to the escape repertoire. If it was meant to be an upgrade to the fear-line, then make it allow Fear to land on mobs under level 58 instead of simply 55. If it *must* be an AE Fear, then at least make it unresistable, work on mobs 55+, and lower its reuse time to somewhere along the lines of 20 minutes.</P><P>AA Flesh to Bone - Personally, this should not have been an AA skill but a spell. Nevertheless, I would say that this is a useful AA skill in the respect that it prevents us from having to farm bonechips and allows us to carry meat around instead of chips. However, this skill, like many of our other spells, is merely a convenience skill. Unlike other classes who receive very real upgrades to their power, necromancers receive a bunch of convenience skills - and the reason is why? Aren't we the ones who are MOST hungry for power from a RPing sense, and most deserving of it in a soloing sense?</P><P>Suggested replacement: none</P><P>AA Innate Invisibility to Undead: This skill is once again a convenience skill, but it is at least more useful than the last one in that it allows us to switch between CoS and IVU rather fast. If no live mobs saw through CoS, and no undead mobs saw through IVU, this would've been a powerful skill indeed. Unfortunately, neither is true. Therefore, this skill is but a minor convenience.</P><P>Suggested replacement: None</P><P>AA Lifeburn: This skill is interesting and grants necromancers a rather unique upgrade to our philosophy of converting hp to mana, and then mana to damage (it converts directly). The problem with this spell is, however, two-fold. First, it does not crit. Second, it has stacking issues. If both of those issues are solved, this skill could indeed become a good, solid AA skill that upgrades our raid-based powers. </P><P>Suggested replacement: None, but fix it please</P><P>AA Mass Group Buff: This is an insult to our class. The only spell that this would actually be used for is Dead Men Floating. Dead Men Floating is just about the rarest spell in the game. Not only is this AA skill so absurdly situational as to be ridiculous, but it depends on us possessing a spell that is so absurdly rare as to be stupid. </P><P>Suggested replacement: The ONLY way to make this useful is to allow it to work with group taps. With a 72 min reuse time, and possibly DOUBLE the mana cost, I don't see ANYTHING unbalancing with allowing a couple of necros to hit the entire raid with Mind Wrack and/or Zevfeers every 72 minutes. Ignore this if it already works with group taps - I honestly don't know any necro with this skill so it's hard for me to verify anything.</P><P>AA Mend Companion: Again, a convenience skill. While "nice to have", it does not change the dynamics of our class at all. Moreover, I just don't understand why VI had to place a 144-minute reuse time on this skill. If it was more in the range of 30-40 minutes, it'd be at least acceptable, but with a 144-minute reuse time it is just a toy, nothing more. It adds very little to our class and there's no real eagerness to get this skill at all.</P><P>Suggested improvement: Other than the reuse time, I suggest looking at a skill that improves the efficiency of Shadowbound/PoS, or an "uber" version of those two spells (1500 hp in 1 minute, for example), much like Cannibalize V is an uber version of Cannibalize.</P><P>AA Pet Discipline: This should not have been an AA skill but something inherent in the game. Aside from that gripe, however, this is a very useful AA skill - except it isn't a necro-class AA skill per say, but a general pet-class AA (mages get it as well). It does not really improve our power but does make it alot easier to control pets on raids. A convenience skill, IMO, like so many of other AA skills, and also one that should've been default in the game. </P><P>Suggested replacement: None, but I don't think it should cost 6 AA skills.</P><P>Summary: Out of all of our AA skills, all but two are convenience skills. Of the two that honestly add power to the class, one is partially broken (Lifeburn), and the other is very situational (Dire Charm). Neither are, at this moment, worth their cost in AA points. In my opinion, our "best" AA skills are the caster archetypes, which in my eyes is a failure on VI's part.</P><P>Are there other classes with broken AA skills? Yes, yes there are, but there are also other classes who have received simply incredible AA skills. As a necromancer, who still believes that his class should be the master of soloing, I do envy a skill like Manaburn or Dire Charm where one could then go off and farm dragons and solo the entire Kael arena. However, I do not need or want them. All I want for necromancers is one decent, awe-inspiring NECROMANCER AA skill. Not a watered down version of the enchanter's Dire Charm, not a life-based Manaburn, but a skill worthy and unique to this class that I have played for 3 years. I'd like to think that VI at least owes each class that much - to give them a unique, class-defining AA skill to pride themselves over, instead of living in the shadows of the AA skills of other classes.</P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed</font></td>
      </tr>
